example.p:
If we take the log of both sides of f(x) = kx^p, we get
\log(f(x)) \amp= \log(kx^p) \log(f(x)) \amp= \log(k)+ \log(x^p) \underset{y}{\log(f(x))} \amp= \underset{m}{p} \cdot \underset{x}{\log(x)} + \underset{y_0}{\log(k)}
This shows us that if our data fits a power function, then we can plot \log(f(x)) as our output and \log(x) as our input and the resulting graph should be linear. Moreover, the slope of the linear function will be the power p and the y-intercept of the linear function will be \log(k).

We will compute trigonometric values of \dfrac{2\pi}{3}. The first step is to identify the picture of \dfrac{2\pi}{3} in the unit circle:

		Then angle 2 pi over 3 sketched in the unit circle.   

As the picture shows, we can then draw a right triangle within the unit circle by drawing a vertical line down to the input axis. We can then determine all of the angles of the triangle, and fill in each length, which tells us the coordinates of the point on the unit circle. Pay attention to whether the coordinates are positive or negative! These are exactly what define, sine, cosine, and tangent of the angle:

		\cos\left(\dfrac{2\pi}{3}\right) \amp=- \dfrac{1}{2} 
		\sin\left(\dfrac{2\pi}{3}\right) \amp=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} 
		\tan\left(\dfrac{2\pi}{3}\right) \amp=\dfrac{\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} - 0 }{- \dfrac{1}{2} - 0} = -\sqrt{3}

Consider the updating function b_{t+1} = 2b_t with initial value b_0= 3. Written as a difference equation, this becomes
	b_{t+1} -b_t = b_t .
Since the average rates of change of b_t are not constant, we know that b_t cannot be a linear function. However, if we look at the ratio of consecutive average rates of change (Fact), we compute

		\dfrac{AROC_{[t+1,t+2]}}{AROC_{[t,t+1]}} \amp= \dfrac{b_{t+2} - b_{t+1}}{b_{t+1} - b_t}  
		 \amp= \dfrac{b_{t+1}}{b_t}
		\amp= \dfrac{2b_t}{b_t}
		\amp= 2

This shows that a solution function of the form b_t = v \cdot 2^t + u would fit the discrete system described by the updating function b_{t+1} = 2b_t. Create a table similar to that of Table using the updating function to verify that the solution function is described by b_t = 3 \cdot 2^t.

subsection.p:
We would like to have an updating function that describes the relationship p_t. That is, we want an equation of the form p_{t+1} = f(p_t). Towards that end, we compute

		p_{t+1} \amp= \dfrac{x_{t+1}}{x_{t+1} + y_{t+1}}
		 \amp= \dfrac{sx_t}{sx_t + ry_t}
		 \amp= \dfrac{sx_t}{sx_t + ry_t} \cdot \dfrac{\frac{1}{x_t + y_t}}{\frac{1}{x_t + y_t}}
		 \amp= \dfrac{s\frac{x_t}{x_t + y_t}}{s\frac{x_t}{x_t + y_t} + r\frac{y_t}{x_t + y_t}} 
		\amp= \dfrac{sp_t}{sp_t +r(1-p_t)}
		\amp= \dfrac{sp_t}{r +(s-r)p_t}

We summarize the development of this competing species model below:

		Competing Species Model
		discrete-time dynamical systemcompeting species model


		If species 1 grows with per capita growth rate s and species 2 grows with per capita growth rate r, the population proportion of species 1 is modeled by the updating function
			p_{t+1} = \dfrac{sp_t}{r+ (s-r)p_t}.


We note here that the competing species model is an example of a discrete-time dynamical systemupdating functionnon-linear non-linear updating function. That is, the updating function rule f(x) = \dfrac{sx}{r+(s-r)x} is not a linear function. This can make finding equilibrium values algebraically more complex, and also allow us to have multiple different equilibrium values. The type of equations that are most relevant for us to be able to solve in this section are quadratic equations quadratic equations. You can find a nice review with solutions of solving quadratic equations at Paul's Online Notes,  Part 1  and  Part 2 .
